#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:3
msgid "Typing (:mod:`numpy.typing`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:7
msgid ""
"Large parts of the NumPy API have :pep:`484`-style type annotations. In "
"addition a number of type aliases are available to users, most prominently "
"the two below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:11
msgid "`ArrayLike`: objects that can be converted to arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:12
msgid "`DTypeLike`: objects that can be converted to dtypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:17
msgid "Mypy plugin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/mypy_plugin.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing.mypy_plugin:1
msgid ""
"A mypy_ plugin for managing a number of platform-specific annotations. Its "
"functionality can be split into three distinct parts:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/mypy_plugin.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing.mypy_plugin:4
msgid ""
"Assigning the (platform-dependent) precisions of certain `~numpy.number` "
"subclasses, including the likes of `~numpy.int_`, `~numpy.intp` and `~numpy."
"longlong`. See the documentation on :ref:`scalar types <arrays.scalars.built-"
"in>` for a comprehensive overview of the affected classes. Without the "
"plugin the precision of all relevant classes will be inferred as `~typing."
"Any`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/mypy_plugin.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing.mypy_plugin:10
msgid ""
"Removing all extended-precision `~numpy.number` subclasses that are "
"unavailable for the platform in question. Most notably this includes the "
"likes of `~numpy.float128` and `~numpy.complex256`. Without the plugin *all* "
"extended-precision types will, as far as mypy is concerned, be available to "
"all platforms."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/mypy_plugin.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing.mypy_plugin:15
msgid ""
"Assigning the (platform-dependent) precision of `~numpy.ctypeslib.c_intp`. "
"Without the plugin the type will default to `ctypes.c_int64`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/mypy_plugin.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing.mypy_plugin:20
msgid ""
"The :mod:`numpy.typing.mypy_plugin` entry-point is deprecated in favor of "
"platform-agnostic static type inference. Remove ``numpy.typing.mypy_plugin`` "
"from the ``plugins`` section of your mypy configuration; if that surfaces "
"new errors, please open an issue with a minimal reproducer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:204 numpy.typing:240 numpy.typing:263
#: numpy.typing.NBitBase:27
#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/mypy_plugin.py:docstring
#: numpy.typing.mypy_plugin:28
msgid "Examples"
msgstr "範例"

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/mypy_plugin.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing.mypy_plugin:29
msgid ""
"To enable the plugin, one must add it to their mypy `configuration file`_:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/mypy_plugin.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing.mypy_plugin:31
msgid ""
"[mypy]\n"
"plugins = numpy.typing.mypy_plugin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:26
msgid "Differences from the runtime NumPy API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:28
msgid ""
"NumPy is very flexible. Trying to describe the full range of possibilities "
"statically would result in types that are not very helpful. For that reason, "
"the typed NumPy API is often stricter than the runtime NumPy API. This "
"section describes some notable differences."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:35
msgid "ArrayLike"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:37
msgid ""
"The `ArrayLike` type tries to avoid creating object arrays. For example,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:40
msgid ""
">>> np.array(x**2 for x in range(10))\n"
"array(<generator object <genexpr> at ...>, dtype=object)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:45
msgid ""
"is valid NumPy code which will create a 0-dimensional object array. Type "
"checkers will complain about the above example when using the NumPy types "
"however. If you really intended to do the above, then you can either use a "
"``# type: ignore`` comment:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:50
msgid ">>> np.array(x**2 for x in range(10))  # type: ignore"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:54
msgid "or explicitly type the array like object as `~typing.Any`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:56
msgid ""
">>> from typing import Any\n"
">>> array_like: Any = (x**2 for x in range(10))\n"
">>> np.array(array_like)\n"
"array(<generator object <genexpr> at ...>, dtype=object)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:64
msgid "ndarray"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:66
msgid ""
"It's possible to mutate the dtype of an array at runtime. For example, the "
"following code is valid:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:69
msgid ""
">>> x = np.array([1, 2])\n"
">>> x.dtype = np.bool"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:74
msgid ""
"This sort of mutation is not allowed by the types. Users who want to write "
"statically typed code should instead use the `numpy.ndarray.view` method to "
"create a view of the array with a different dtype."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:79
msgid "DTypeLike"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:81
msgid ""
"The `DTypeLike` type tries to avoid creation of dtype objects using "
"dictionary of fields like below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:84
msgid ">>> x = np.dtype({\"field1\": (float, 1), \"field2\": (int, 3)})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:88
msgid ""
"Although this is valid NumPy code, the type checker will complain about it, "
"since its usage is discouraged. Please see : :ref:`Data type objects <arrays."
"dtypes>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:93
msgid "Number precision"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:95
msgid ""
"The precision of `numpy.number` subclasses is treated as a invariant generic "
"parameter (see :class:`~NBitBase`), simplifying the annotating of processes "
"involving precision-based casting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:99
msgid ""
">>> from typing import TypeVar\n"
">>> import numpy as np\n"
">>> import numpy.typing as npt\n"
"\n"
">>> T = TypeVar(\"T\", bound=npt.NBitBase)\n"
">>> def func(a: np.floating[T], b: np.floating[T]) -> np.floating[T]:\n"
"...     ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:109
msgid ""
"Consequently, the likes of `~numpy.float16`, `~numpy.float32` and `~numpy."
"float64` are still sub-types of `~numpy.floating`, but, contrary to runtime, "
"they're not necessarily considered as sub-classes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:113
msgid ""
"The :class:`~numpy.typing.NBitBase` helper is deprecated and will be  "
"removed in a future release. Prefer expressing precision relationships via  "
"``typing.overload`` or ``TypeVar`` definitions bounded by concrete scalar  "
"classes. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:119
msgid ""
"from typing import TypeVar\n"
"import numpy as np\n"
"\n"
"S = TypeVar(\"S\", bound=np.floating)\n"
"\n"
"def func(a: S, b: S) -> S:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:129
msgid ""
"or in the case of different input types mapping to different output types:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:131
msgid ""
"from typing import overload\n"
"import numpy as np\n"
"\n"
"@overload\n"
"def phase(x: np.complex64) -> np.float32: ...\n"
"@overload\n"
"def phase(x: np.complex128) -> np.float64: ...\n"
"@overload\n"
"def phase(x: np.clongdouble) -> np.longdouble: ...\n"
"def phase(x: np.complexfloating) -> np.floating:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:146
msgid "Timedelta64"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:148
msgid ""
"The `~numpy.timedelta64` class is not considered a subclass of `~numpy."
"signedinteger`, the former only inheriting from `~numpy.generic` while "
"static type checking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:153
msgid "0D arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:155
msgid ""
"During runtime numpy aggressively casts any passed 0D arrays into their "
"corresponding `~numpy.generic` instance. Until the introduction of shape "
"typing (see :pep:`646`) it is unfortunately not possible to make the "
"necessary distinction between 0D and >0D arrays. While thus not strictly "
"correct, all operations that can potentially perform a 0D-array -> scalar "
"cast are currently annotated as exclusively returning an `~numpy.ndarray`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:162
msgid ""
"If it is known in advance that an operation *will* perform a 0D-array -> "
"scalar cast, then one can consider manually remedying the situation with "
"either `typing.cast` or a ``# type: ignore`` comment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:167
msgid "Record array dtypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:169
msgid ""
"The dtype of `numpy.recarray`, and the :ref:`routines.array-creation.rec` "
"functions in general, can be specified in one of two ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:172
msgid "Directly via the ``dtype`` argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:173
msgid ""
"With up to five helper arguments that operate via `numpy.rec.format_parser`: "
"``formats``, ``names``, ``titles``, ``aligned`` and ``byteorder``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/typing/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.typing:176
msgid ""
"These two approaches are currently typed as being mutually exclusive, *i.e.* "
"if ``dtype`` is specified than one may not specify ``formats``. While this "
"mutual exclusivity is not (strictly) enforced during runtime, combining both "
"dtype specifiers can lead to unexpected or even downright buggy behavior."
msgstr ""

